ce:abstract-sec.ce:simple-para:
A method for the quantification of 22–26 nm gold (AuNP) and 10–20 nm silver nanoparticles (AgNP) was developed using the fluorescence quenching of rhodamine-6G. This fluorescent probe detected the different metal nanoparticles (MNP) at the pmol L−1 level (3.6 to 15.6 pmol L−1) depending on the type of nanoparticle) in phosphate buffer solutions at pH 6.94. The method was validated at the 95% confidence level using recovery tests to spiked drinking and surface river water (before and after industries). For AuNP26
                     @citrate and AgNP12
                     @SDDC, the overall average recoveries (



                                 R


                                 ¯



                     ) were 90% (RSD: 11%) and 82% (RSD: 10%) in drinking water, respectively. Whereas, in surface river water before and after industries, 



                                 R


                                 ¯



                      were 88% (RSD: 17%) and 93% (RSD: 11%) for AuNP26
                     @citrate, correspondingly; and 94% (RSD: 6%) and 83% (12%) for AgNP12
                     @SDDC, respectively. The proposed strategy represents an accurate, rapid, simple, and cost-effective methodology to analyze MNP in aqueous systems.

ce:section.ce:para:
The fluorescence emission of both Rh, 6G (Rh6G), and B (RhB), was measured in the presence of AuNP22
                        @citrate and AgNP18
                        @gallic to determine which fluorescent probe was more sensitive to the analytes. The chosen concentrations of Rh6G and RhB were 0.4 μmol L-1 and 0.55 μmol L-1, respectively, in order to keep the absorbance value lower than 0.05 whilst obtaining a reliable fluorescence intensity. AuNP22
                        @citrate and AgNP18
                        @gallic quenched the luminescence signals of Rh6G and RhB either in water (not shown) or in 0.01 mol L-1 phosphate buffer pH 6.94 (Fig. 2
                         is representative), but in different extent. The presence of N and O in the chemical structures of both Rh facilitates the interaction with the metal surface [20], and at very short distances (<5 nm), the fluorescence emission is depleted [25,38]. Two main mechanisms are usually responsible for this quenching phenomenon, the FRET, where the nanoparticle behaves as a dipole; and the surface energy transfer (SET), where the MNP behaves more like a metal surface without the need of resonance electronic transitions between donor and acceptor [39–41]. The partial overlapping between the emission spectrum of the Rhs and the surface plasmon band of the AuNP favors the energy transfer between both compounds, producing the quenching phenomenon in a FRET-like mechanism. However, both FRET and SET are likely to be operating similarly to the observed for the system Rh6G:AuNP@PVA (25–70 nm) [40]. In the case of AgNP, where the spectral overlap to Rh fluorescence emission is small, the SET mechanism is likely to be predominant as occurs with MNP that do not display a surface plasmon [41], though our studies cannot distinguish between the two mechanisms.

In comparison, Rh6G was 1.7–2.8 times more sensitive to the MNP than RhB, in 0.01 M phosphate buffer at pH 6.94. Also, a similar result was obtained in water. Besides, for Rh6G, the quenching effect was more substantial using buffered solutions (17% for AuNP22
                        @citrate and 100% for AgNP18
                        @gallic) than in water, and on the contrary was observed for RhB (Table S2). After comparing these results, the quenching of Rh6G at pH 6.94 was chosen as the analytical strategy for the detection of MNP, and the method was validated as follows.

In addition to AuNP22
                        @citrate and AgNP18
                        @gallic, Rh6G is also sensitive to AgNP12
                        @SDDC and AuNP26
                        @citrate. Table 1
                         shows the main analytical parameters determined for the four analytes. Analysing the size and polydispersity effect, the SEN was 30% higher for the 26 nm compared to 22 nm AuNP@citrate. Besides, this parameter was 3.5 times larger for AgNP12
                        @SDDC than for AgNP18
                        @gallic, indicating also the effect of the ligand on the MNP surface. For each analyte, the validity of the linear model operating between the variables F0/F and [MNP] was corroborated at the 95% confidence level (p < 0.05) using the F-test for significance of regression based on ANOVA [42]. Also, using the analysis of residuals in regression the normality and homoscedasticity assumptions were verified [43].

For all the analytes, the LODs and LOQs were in the picomolar order. In agreement with the SEN values, the lowest LOD were obtained for both types of AuNP and AgNP12
                        @SDDC, followed by AgNP18
                        @gallic.

Selectivity was evaluated using foreign species like inorganic salts and other MNP as potential interferences. Table 3
                         shows the tolerance (T) calculated as the interference/analyte concentration ratio that produced a 10% error in the expected Rh6G fluorescence. The tolerance of the system Rh6G:AuNP22
                        @citrate was excellent to the presence of common inorganic salts (T > 1010), including the gold precursor Au3+ (T = 105), but low to the occurrence of AgNP12
                        @SDDC (0.26). For its part, the system Rh6G:AgNP12
                        @SDDC also showed a high tolerance to inorganic salts (T > 109) and the silver precursor Ag+ (T = 105), but low to AuNP22@citrate (T = 0.13) and AgNP18
                        @gallic (T = 1.06), respectively. The low tolerance to other MNP was expected as the Rh6G is sensitive to both of them with similar LOD. Another technique for identification purposes in an unknown sample, like absorption spectroscopy in the SPB region, could discard the presence of more than one type of MNP [52].

Due to the numerous MNP applications, they are likely to be released direct or indirectly into the aquatic environment, and as a consequence, to quantify their concentrations in such matrices is of high importance [3,4,53,54]. In absence of Certified Reference Materials for each nanoparticle and reference methods, the analytical procedure was validated for AuNP26
                        @citrate and AgNP12
                        @SDDC by application to recovery tests from spiked matrices [13,55] (Tables 4 and 5

                        , respectively) of drinking water from the Córdoba distribution network and surface water from the Ctalamochita river. The matrix blank did not modify the Rh6G fluorescence emission in any case. Table 4 shows the recoveries obtained for AuNP26
                        @citrate in the three different spiked matrices, giving satisfactory apparent recovery values in tap water and BI-RW (Table 4). However, in the case of AI-RW, a slight negative matrix effect was observed, that was solved by performing the calibration curve in the presence of 10% v/v AI-RW (Figure S2) before running new recovery assays (Table 4). The lower SEN value obtained with 10% v/v AI-RW is likely due to the presence of unknown compounds that can also interact with the AuNP resulting in a minor quenching on the Rh6G fluorescence emission. For AgNP12
                        @SDDC, the SEN value used in the calculus of recovery assays accounted for potential differences between MNP batches (Table 5).

We also wondered how MNP aging could affect the methods’ robustness. To further examine this, the recovery assays were performed on one-year aged AuNP22
                        @citrate (Table S3). Although the effect on size distribution was slight (Figure S3), the Rh6G quenching showed a smaller SEN value compared to the fresh MNP. Still, the recovery assays showed good results (Table S3) comparable to others reported for the quantification of AuNP in environmental samples [41,46]. The 



                                    R


                                    ¯



                         value for the aged AuNP22
                        @citrate was 103% (18%; BI-RW) and 97% (10%, AI-RW), and using a two-tail test-t, it was also concluded that the analytical method was accurate at the 95% confidence level.

In conclusion, an alternative, rapid, simple and cost-effective analytical strategy for quantification of MNP, based on the chemical sensing concept, is proposed. The fluorescence quenching of Rh6G due to non-covalent interactions with the selected MNP in phosphate buffer permit their quantification at the picomolar level, making it competitive with other reported methods. Size and ligands on the MNP surface affect the observed quenching of Rh6G fluorescence, being more sensitive for AuNP26
                     @citrate and AgNP12
                     @SDDC. Also, the sensing system showed high tolerance to common inorganic salts and also to Au3+ and Ag+ ions, precursors of the analysed MNP. The method is accurate at a 95% confidence level for quantification of AuNP@citrate (fresh or aged) and AgNP@SDDC in tap water and surface river waters as potential environmental samples of analysis.
